Heh,<br>
I know that page 18 is hardly the time to start pouring gasoline on the fire for this type of thread, but... (and nothing matters before the but) <br>
What is religion anyway?<br>
I mean, call me Clinton-esque here, but I have yet to see a formal assertion of what religion means to the arguing participants. <br>
<br>
Is religion lifestyle?<br>
Is religion morality?<br>
Is religion simply the idea of something after death?<br>
To you, does law of government hold more importance than law of religion?<br>
Which parts of your religious teachings are more important than the others? Who determines the hierarchy of relevance?<br>
Does your religion change over time?  Why?<br>
Why are some people gifted to authorize the teachings of the religion and other denied?<br>
<br>
I have my own ideas about things. <br>
I don't know how many of them are in line with yours. <br>
Can we debate whose ideas might be correct?  Of course.<br>
Can we prove that some ideas are better than others?  I doubt it.<br>
It all depends on your perspective, you see. <br>
Personally, I don't think flattening my penis with a mallet and driving a spike through it is a good idea...  some people, however, do. <br>
Both sides of the argument will make their points, but in the end it is very unlikely that I will be buying a hammer and nails from my local hardware store with self-mutilation in mind, no matter how logical the assertions of the other party. <br>
<br>
So, Zozz, what's your point? <br>
My point is this:<br>
The lines of religion are lightly sketched rather than drawn clearly.  The teachings of various religions change over time and have many different variations even within the same larger faith umbrella.  Many people will spend their entire lives examining religion and its role in their life.  Some people will change religion many times.   The idea of coming to this thread spouting your opinion (pro-christianity, atheist, buddhist, or church of the holy poutine) and expecting people to immediately reexamine their own beliefs is ridiculous. <br>
So say your piece and expect nothing more than what you would give yourself.<br>
<br>
(and yes, I also realize that expecting people to behave differently as a result of a post my me is similarly pointless, but given my genetics and sum total of environmental stimuli, I was compelled to write this despite my stubborn ego-centric belief in the illusion of free will)<br>
<br>
Zozz<br>
